{"type":"message","id":"9ad05460","parentId":"f4db891b","timestamp":"2026-04-16T01:27:45.571Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The BE process is not running anymore (it crashed). And the log shows it was still using the old MongoDB URI. The issue is that `ts-node-dev` was running and when I ran `fuser -k 5555/tcp`, it killed the old process. Then I started a new process with the new .env. But the new process crashed immediately because it couldn't connect.\n\nActually wait - I started the new process BEFORE I fixed the .env. So the sequence was:\n1. First restart (killed old, started new with old .env that had `103.253.21.98:27017`) → still connecting to remote\n\n\n2. Fixed .env to `localhost:27017`\n3. Killed old, started new → crashed immediately\n\nThe crash dump is from the second process that started after I fixed the .env, but it's still trying to connect to the old remote IP, which means either the .env fix didn't take effect or there's a cached config somewhere that ts-node-dev is using.\n\nThe error timestamp shows it crashed at `01:26:46.857Z`, which is about a minute after I made the change at `01:25:17Z`. Since `ts-node-dev` watches for file changes and reloads automatically, it should've picked up the .env update, but it looks like the hot reload triggered a restart that's hitting the old configuration anyway. But ts-node-dev should have reloaded the .env after I changed it. The fact that it still connects to `103.253.21.98` means either the hot reload didn't work or there's a different issue.\n\nActually, looking at the timestamps more carefully: the first process started at 01:25:17 (from the first restart command). The .env was changed around 01:25:17-01:25:20. The crash happened at 01:26:46. But process 342361 (the one I started after the .env fix) - did it start at 01:25:17 or later? The first restart command I ran killed the old process and started a new one, but then I killed that one and started again after fixing .env, so I need to trace through the exact sequence of commands and their timing to figure out which process crashed and why.\n\nThe crash log shows the MongoDB URI is still pointing to the remote host, which means either the new process didn't pick up the updated .env file, or ts-node-dev's hot reload didn't trigger properly. The BE process is now dead, so I need to restart it with the correct local MongoDB URI. But there's another problem - the .env has `MONGODB_USER=root` and `MONGODB_PASS=RYLoQJqsDr4EQIJB`, which are credentials for the remote MongoDB, so even if I fix the URI to localhost, those credentials might not work with the local instance. I should check if the local MongoDB even has authentication enabled.","thinkingSignature":"ab229a7ebada8856cc9d8558d118d4ce2468ed9b495bb2f79c6494edb6535bfd"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_hfuc9w6udx54_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"# Check if local MongoDB has auth\ndocker ps 2>/dev/null | grep mongo || echo \"Docker mongo\"\ndocker exec $(docker ps -q --filter ancestor=mongo 2>/dev/null | head -1) mongod --version 2>/dev/null || echo \"Cannot exec\"\n# Try connecting without auth\npython3 -c \"\nimport urllib.request, json\ntry:\n    r = urllib.request.urlopen('http://localhost:27017/', timeout=3)\n    print('MongoDB accessible without auth')\nexcept Exception as e:\n    print(f'MongoDB: {e}')\n\" 2>/dev/null || echo \"curl failed\"\n\n# Check if local MongoDB has the dtlx database\ndocker exec $(docker ps -q --filter \"ancestor=mongo\" | head -1) mongosh --quiet --eval \"use admin; db.runCommand({ping:1})\" 2>/dev/null || echo \"Cannot ping\""}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"ahvholding","model":"AHV-Holding-DEV","usage":{"input":361,"output":836,"cacheRead":114483,"cacheWrite":606,"totalTokens":116286,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776302844216,"responseId":"062f6dfdd2c81eddd3e5cc83404f7bb9"}}
